            "body": "<p>Check out <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/util/Set.html\" rel=\"nofollow\" title=\"Sets\">Sets<\/a>, they're like Lists, but they have the ability to be unique inside the object. I.e. if you have:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>Set&lt;Integer&gt; intSet = new HashSet&lt;Integer&gt;()\nintSet.add(1);\nintSet.add(1);\nfor (Integer i : intSet) {\n     System.out.println(i);\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>The final output should be:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>1\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Sets don't allow multiple Identical Objects in the same set.<\/p>\n\n<p>Also, When you were declaring your ArrayLists, be sure to note what kind of an ArrayList each one is, otherwise your IDE should be yelling at you, but I think it defaults to Object. I recommend having a custom model object if you need 3 fields in the Set/List and declare it like this <code>List&lt;CustomModelObject&gt; listOfObjects = new ArrayList&lt;CustomModelObject&gt;();<\/code> (see above example if you need an example for Set)<\/p>\n",
